726361f-a.text:
Colonial Ave., (right side of house not shown) west side, orth of 62nd Drive. If locating in 1922, it would be on Mill Creek nd Old Mill Road. At the street line of the S.W. corner of orace Hiarding Boulevard and Colonial Avenue is the site of this ouse which was rased in Sept 193O to make way for the Horace arding Boulevard. Judge Robert Coe erected the house in 1655. he following year he moved to Jamaica and Captain John Coe beame the owner of the farmhouse and the Mill property which was n the west side of the Creek. In 1698 Judge John Coe, 2nd son f Captain John Coe was the owner. This family retained possession or almost a century when about 1810 David Titus became the owner. e in turn sold to Daniel Rapelye son of Major Rapelye who was till the o.mer in 1852. Mrs. Nenny was an occupant in 1922. ugene L. Armbruster states that the Lott farily also owned this rop-rty. The mill was destroyed by fire in 1875. L. J. Wood, . Felton, or R. v. Hitchcock was the owner in 1873. The present tructure was erected about 1750 on the site of the old house. ne Van Rieper however states it to be the original Coe house. ne Earll was the owner of this property in 188O. Thomas G. Smith f the Shady Lake farm was the owner in 1910. According to igures inscribed on a stone in the building, the house was said n 1925 to be 216 years old. View No. 3 shows the house at the
ight background. Mill Creek is in the foreground.
Jan. 1926
Views 1, 2 and 3.
Vgene L. Armbruster Collection

726373f-b.text:
Colonial Avenue, (electric light poles thereon), north from 62nd Drive to Nassau Boulevard. In the foreground of View No. 1 is Mill Creek, flowing north eastward to Flushing Creek. At the left; windows projecting from roof; is the Richard Coe farmhouse. Across the way is the De La Corte Inn. In the background are the Flushing ash dumps. View No. 2 is looking south from the Boulevard and shows the renovated inn. View No. 3 shows a closeup of the Old Inn which was erected in 1883; No. 4 shows the renovation of the house; with the Flushing dumps just beyond it.
